45 // Return true if Expr is in the range [MinValue, MaxValue]. If AllowSymbol ----
46 // is true any MCExpr is accepted (address displacement). ----
47 static bool inRange(const MCExpr *Expr, int64_t MinValue, int64_t MaxValue, 0
48 bool AllowSymbol = false) { ----
49 if (auto *CE = dyn_cast(Expr)) { 0
50 int64_t Value = CE->getValue(); 0
51 return Value >= MinValue && Value <= MaxValue; 0
52 } ----
53 return AllowSymbol; 0
54 } ----

81 class SystemZOperand : public MCParsedAsmOperand { ----
82 private: ----
83 enum OperandKind { ----
84 KindInvalid, ----
85 KindToken, ----
86 KindReg, ----
87 KindImm, ----
88 KindImmTLS, ----
89 KindMem ----
90 }; ----
91 ----
92 OperandKind Kind; ----
93 SMLoc StartLoc, EndLoc; ----
94 ----
95 // A string of length Length, starting at Data. ----
96 struct TokenOp { ----
97 const char *Data; ----
98 unsigned Length; ----
99 }; ----
100 ----
101 // LLVM register Num, which has kind Kind. In some ways it might be ----
102 // easier for this class to have a register bank (general, floating-point ----
103 // or access) and a raw register number (0-15). This would postpone the ----
104 // interpretation of the operand to the add*() methods and avoid the need ----
105 // for context-dependent parsing. However, we do things the current way ----
106 // because of the virtual getReg() method, which needs to distinguish ----
107 // between (say) %r0 used as a single register and %r0 used as a pair. ----
108 // Context-dependent parsing can also give us slightly better error ----
109 // messages when invalid pairs like %r1 are used. ----
110 struct RegOp { ----
111 RegisterKind Kind; ----
112 unsigned Num; ----
113 }; ----
114 ----
115 // Base + Disp + Index, where Base and Index are LLVM registers or 0. ----
116 // MemKind says what type of memory this is and RegKind says what type ----
117 // the base register has (GR32Reg or GR64Reg). Length is the operand ----
118 // length for D(L,B)-style operands, otherwise it is null. ----
119 struct MemOp { ----
120 unsigned Base : 12; ----
121 unsigned Index : 12; ----
122 unsigned MemKind : 4; ----
123 unsigned RegKind : 4; ----
124 const MCExpr *Disp; ----
125 union { ----
126 const MCExpr *Imm; ----
127 unsigned Reg; ----
128 } Length; ----
129 }; ----
130 ----
131 // Imm is an immediate operand, and Sym is an optional TLS symbol ----
132 // for use with a __tls_get_offset marker relocation. ----
133 struct ImmTLSOp { ----
134 const MCExpr *Imm; ----
135 const MCExpr *Sym; ----
136 }; ----
137 ----
138 union { ----
139 TokenOp Token; ----
140 RegOp Reg; ----
141 const MCExpr *Imm; ----
142 ImmTLSOp ImmTLS; ----
143 MemOp Mem; ----
144 }; ----
145 ----
146 void addExpr(MCInst &Inst, const MCExpr *Expr) const { 0
147 // Add as immediates when possible. Null MCExpr = 0. ----
148 if (!Expr) 0
149 Inst.addOperand(MCOperand::createImm(0)); 0
150 else if (auto *CE = dyn_cast(Expr)) 0
151 Inst.addOperand(MCOperand::createImm(CE->getValue())); 0
152 else ----
153 Inst.addOperand(MCOperand::createExpr(Expr)); 0
154 } 0
155 ----
156 public: ----
157 SystemZOperand(OperandKind kind, SMLoc startLoc, SMLoc endLoc) 0
158 : Kind(kind), StartLoc(startLoc), EndLoc(endLoc) {} 0

160 // Create particular kinds of operand. ----
161 static std::unique_ptr createInvalid(SMLoc StartLoc, 0
162 SMLoc EndLoc) { ----
163 return std::make_unique(KindInvalid, StartLoc, EndLoc); 0
164 } ----
165 ----
166 static std::unique_ptr createToken(StringRef Str, SMLoc Loc) { 0
167 auto Op = std::make_unique(KindToken, Loc, Loc); 0
168 Op->Token.Data = Str.data(); 0
169 Op->Token.Length = Str.size(); 0
170 return Op; 0
171 } ----
172 ----
173 static std::unique_ptr ----
174 createReg(RegisterKind Kind, unsigned Num, SMLoc StartLoc, SMLoc EndLoc) { 0
175 auto Op = std::make_unique(KindReg, StartLoc, EndLoc); 0
176 Op->Reg.Kind = Kind; 0
177 Op->Reg.Num = Num; 0
178 return Op; 0
179 } ----
180 ----
181 static std::unique_ptr ----
182 createImm(const MCExpr *Expr, SMLoc StartLoc, SMLoc EndLoc) { 0
183 auto Op = std::make_unique(KindImm, StartLoc, EndLoc); 0
184 Op->Imm = Expr; 0
185 return Op; 0
186 } ----
187 ----
188 static std::unique_ptr ----
189 createMem(MemoryKind MemKind, RegisterKind RegKind, unsigned Base, 0
190 const MCExpr *Disp, unsigned Index, const MCExpr *LengthImm, ----
191 unsigned LengthReg, SMLoc StartLoc, SMLoc EndLoc) { ----
192 auto Op = std::make_unique(KindMem, StartLoc, EndLoc); 0
193 Op->Mem.MemKind = MemKind; 0
194 Op->Mem.RegKind = RegKind; 0
195 Op->Mem.Base = Base; 0
196 Op->Mem.Index = Index; 0
197 Op->Mem.Disp = Disp; 0
198 if (MemKind == BDLMem) 0
199 Op->Mem.Length.Imm = LengthImm; 0
200 if (MemKind == BDRMem) 0
201 Op->Mem.Length.Reg = LengthReg; 0
202 return Op; 0
203 } ----
204 ----
205 static std::unique_ptr ----
206 createImmTLS(const MCExpr *Imm, const MCExpr *Sym, 0
207 SMLoc StartLoc, SMLoc EndLoc) { ----
208 auto Op = std::make_unique(KindImmTLS, StartLoc, EndLoc); 0
209 Op->ImmTLS.Imm = Imm; 0
210 Op->ImmTLS.Sym = Sym; 0
211 return Op; 0
212 } ----

214 // Token operands ----
215 bool isToken() const override { 0
216 return Kind == KindToken; 0
217 } ----
218 StringRef getToken() const { 0
219 assert(Kind == KindToken && "Not a token"); 0
220 return StringRef(Token.Data, Token.Length); 0
221 } ----

223 // Register operands. ----
224 bool isReg() const override { 0
225 return Kind == KindReg; 0
226 } ----
227 bool isReg(RegisterKind RegKind) const { 0
228 return Kind == KindReg && Reg.Kind == RegKind; 0
229 } ----
230 unsigned getReg() const override { 0
231 assert(Kind == KindReg && "Not a register"); 0
232 return Reg.Num; 0
233 } ----
234 ----
235 // Immediate operands. ----
236 bool isImm() const override { 0
237 return Kind == KindImm; 0
238 } ----
239 bool isImm(int64_t MinValue, int64_t MaxValue) const { 0
240 return Kind == KindImm && inRange(Imm, MinValue, MaxValue, true); 0
241 } ----
242 const MCExpr *getImm() const { 0
243 assert(Kind == KindImm && "Not an immediate"); 0
244 return Imm; 0
245 } ----

248 bool isImmTLS() const { 0
249 return Kind == KindImmTLS; 0
250 } ----
251 ----
252 const ImmTLSOp getImmTLS() const { 0
253 assert(Kind == KindImmTLS && "Not a TLS immediate"); 0
254 return ImmTLS; 0
255 } ----

257 // Memory operands. ----
258 bool isMem() const override { 0
259 return Kind == KindMem; 0
260 } ----
261 bool isMem(MemoryKind MemKind) const { 0
262 return (Kind == KindMem && 0
263 (Mem.MemKind == MemKind || 0
264 // A BDMem can be treated as a BDXMem in which the index ----
265 // register field is 0. ----
266 (Mem.MemKind == BDMem && MemKind == BDXMem))); 0
267 } ----
268 bool isMem(MemoryKind MemKind, RegisterKind RegKind) const { 0
269 return isMem(MemKind) && Mem.RegKind == RegKind; 0
270 } ----
271 bool isMemDisp12(MemoryKind MemKind, RegisterKind RegKind) const { 0
272 return isMem(MemKind, RegKind) && inRange(Mem.Disp, 0, 0xfff, true); 0
273 } ----
274 bool isMemDisp20(MemoryKind MemKind, RegisterKind RegKind) const { 0
275 return isMem(MemKind, RegKind) && inRange(Mem.Disp, -524288, 524287, true); 0
276 } ----
277 bool isMemDisp12Len4(RegisterKind RegKind) const { 0
278 return isMemDisp12(BDLMem, RegKind) && inRange(Mem.Length.Imm, 1, 0x10); 0
279 } ----
280 bool isMemDisp12Len8(RegisterKind RegKind) const { 0
281 return isMemDisp12(BDLMem, RegKind) && inRange(Mem.Length.Imm, 1, 0x100); 0
282 } ----

284 const MemOp& getMem() const { 0
285 assert(Kind == KindMem && "Not a Mem operand"); 0
286 return Mem; 0
287 } ----

300 void addRegOperands(MCInst &Inst, unsigned N) const { 0
301 assert(N == 1 && "Invalid number of operands"); 0
302 Inst.addOperand(MCOperand::createReg(getReg())); 0
303 } 0
304 void addImmOperands(MCInst &Inst, unsigned N) const { 0
305 assert(N == 1 && "Invalid number of operands"); 0
306 addExpr(Inst, getImm()); 0
307 } 0
308 void addBDAddrOperands(MCInst &Inst, unsigned N) const { 0
309 assert(N == 2 && "Invalid number of operands"); 0
310 assert(isMem(BDMem) && "Invalid operand type"); 0
311 Inst.addOperand(MCOperand::createReg(Mem.Base)); 0
312 addExpr(Inst, Mem.Disp); 0
313 } 0

315 assert(N == 3 && "Invalid number of operands"); 0

317 Inst.addOperand(MCOperand::createReg(Mem.Base)); 0

319 Inst.addOperand(MCOperand::createReg(Mem.Index)); 0
320 } 0

323 assert(isMem(BDLMem) && "Invalid operand type"); 0
324 Inst.addOperand(MCOperand::createReg(Mem.Base)); 0
325 addExpr(Inst, Mem.Disp); 0
326 addExpr(Inst, Mem.Length.Imm); 0
327 } 0

334 } 0

341 } 0

343 assert(N == 2 && "Invalid number of operands"); 0
344 assert(Kind == KindImmTLS && "Invalid operand type"); 0

446 // Both the hlasm and att variants still rely on the basic gnu asm ----
447 // format with respect to inputs, clobbers, outputs etc. ----
448 // ----
449 // However, calling the overriden getAssemblerDialect() method in ----
450 // AsmParser is problematic. It either returns the AssemblerDialect field ----
451 // in the MCAsmInfo instance if the AssemblerDialect field in AsmParser is ----
452 // unset, otherwise it returns the private AssemblerDialect field in ----
453 // AsmParser. ----
454 // ----
455 // The problematic part is because, we forcibly set the inline asm dialect ----
456 // in the AsmParser instance in AsmPrinterInlineAsm.cpp. Soo any query ----
457 // to the overriden getAssemblerDialect function in AsmParser.cpp, will ----
458 // not return the assembler dialect set in the respective MCAsmInfo instance. ----
459 // ----
460 // For this purpose, we explicitly query the SystemZMCAsmInfo instance ----
461 // here, to get the "correct" assembler dialect, and use it in various ----
462 // functions. ----
463 unsigned getMAIAssemblerDialect() { 0
464 return Parser.getContext().getAsmInfo()->getAssemblerDialect(); 0
465 } ----
466 ----
467 // An alphabetic character in HLASM is a letter from 'A' through 'Z', ----
468 // or from 'a' through 'z', or '$', '_','#', or '@'. ----
469 inline bool isHLASMAlpha(char C) { 0
470 return isAlpha(C) || llvm::is_contained("_@#$", C); 0
471 } ----
472 ----
473 // A digit in HLASM is a number from 0 to 9. ----
474 inline bool isHLASMAlnum(char C) { return isHLASMAlpha(C) || isDigit(C); } 0
475 ----
476 // Are we parsing using the AD_HLASM dialect? ----
477 inline bool isParsingHLASM() { return getMAIAssemblerDialect() == AD_HLASM; } 0
478 ----
479 // Are we parsing using the AD_ATT dialect? ----
480 inline bool isParsingATT() { return getMAIAssemblerDialect() == AD_ATT; } 0

584 OperandMatchResultTy parseBDVAddr64(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
585 return parseAddress(Operands, BDVMem, GR64Reg); 0
586 } ----
587 OperandMatchResultTy parsePCRel12(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
588 return parsePCRel(Operands, -(1LL << 12), (1LL << 12) - 1, false); 0
589 } ----
590 OperandMatchResultTy parsePCRel16(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
591 return parsePCRel(Operands, -(1LL << 16), (1LL << 16) - 1, false); 0
592 } ----
593 OperandMatchResultTy parsePCRel24(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
594 return parsePCRel(Operands, -(1LL << 24), (1LL << 24) - 1, false); 0
595 } ----
596 OperandMatchResultTy parsePCRel32(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
597 return parsePCRel(Operands, -(1LL << 32), (1LL << 32) - 1, false); 0
598 } ----
599 OperandMatchResultTy parsePCRelTLS16(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
600 return parsePCRel(Operands, -(1LL << 16), (1LL << 16) - 1, true); 0
601 } ----
602 OperandMatchResultTy parsePCRelTLS32(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
603 return parsePCRel(Operands, -(1LL << 32), (1LL << 32) - 1, true); 0
604 } ----
605 }; ----
606 ----
607 } // end anonymous namespace ----

615 // Used for the .insn directives; contains information needed to parse the ----
616 // operands in the directive. ----
617 struct InsnMatchEntry { ----
618 StringRef Format; ----
619 uint64_t Opcode; ----
620 int32_t NumOperands; ----
621 MatchClassKind OperandKinds[7]; ----
622 }; ----
623 ----
624 // For equal_range comparison. ----
625 struct CompareInsn { ----
626 bool operator() (const InsnMatchEntry &LHS, StringRef RHS) { 0
627 return LHS.Format < RHS; 0
628 } ----
629 bool operator() (StringRef LHS, const InsnMatchEntry &RHS) { 0
630 return LHS < RHS.Format; 0
631 } ----
632 bool operator() (const InsnMatchEntry &LHS, const InsnMatchEntry &RHS) { ----
633 return LHS.Format < RHS.Format; ----
634 } ----
635 }; ----

705 static void printMCExpr(const MCExpr *E, raw_ostream &OS) { 0
706 if (!E) 0
707 return; 0
708 if (auto *CE = dyn_cast(E)) 0
709 OS << *CE; 0
710 else if (auto *UE = dyn_cast(E)) 0
711 OS << *UE; 0
712 else if (auto *BE = dyn_cast(E)) 0
713 OS << *BE; 0
714 else if (auto *SRE = dyn_cast(E)) 0
715 OS << *SRE; 0
716 else ----
717 OS << *E; 0
718 } ----
719 ----
720 void SystemZOperand::print(raw_ostream &OS) const { 0
721 switch (Kind) { 0
722 case KindToken: 0
723 OS << "Token:" << getToken(); 0
724 break; 0
725 case KindReg: 0
726 OS << "Reg:" << SystemZInstPrinter::getRegisterName(getReg()); 0
727 break; 0
728 case KindImm: 0
729 OS << "Imm:"; 0
730 printMCExpr(getImm(), OS); 0
731 break; 0
732 case KindImmTLS: 0
733 OS << "ImmTLS:"; 0
734 printMCExpr(getImmTLS().Imm, OS); 0
735 if (getImmTLS().Sym) { 0
736 OS << ", "; 0
737 printMCExpr(getImmTLS().Sym, OS); 0
738 } ----
739 break; 0
740 case KindMem: { 0
741 const MemOp &Op = getMem(); 0
742 OS << "Mem:" << *cast(Op.Disp); 0
743 if (Op.Base) { 0
744 OS << "("; 0
745 if (Op.MemKind == BDLMem) 0
746 OS << *cast(Op.Length.Imm) << ","; 0
747 else if (Op.MemKind == BDRMem) 0
748 OS << SystemZInstPrinter::getRegisterName(Op.Length.Reg) << ","; 0
749 if (Op.Index) 0
750 OS << SystemZInstPrinter::getRegisterName(Op.Index) << ","; 0
751 OS << SystemZInstPrinter::getRegisterName(Op.Base); 0
752 OS << ")"; 0
753 } ----
754 break; 0
755 } ----
756 case KindInvalid: 0
757 break; 0
758 } ----
759 } 0
760 ----
761 // Parse one register of the form %. ----
762 bool SystemZAsmParser::parseRegister(Register &Reg, bool RestoreOnFailure) { 0
763 Reg.StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
764 ----
765 // Eat the % prefix. ----
766 if (Parser.getTok().isNot(AsmToken::Percent)) 0
767 return Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "register expected"); 0
768 const AsmToken &PercentTok = Parser.getTok(); 0
769 Parser.Lex(); 0
770 ----
771 // Expect a register name. ----
772 if (Parser.getTok().isNot(AsmToken::Identifier)) { 0
773 if (RestoreOnFailure) 0
774 getLexer().UnLex(PercentTok); 0
775 return Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid register"); 0
776 } ----
777 ----
778 // Check that there's a prefix. ----
779 StringRef Name = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
780 if (Name.size() < 2) { 0
781 if (RestoreOnFailure) 0
782 getLexer().UnLex(PercentTok); 0
783 return Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid register"); 0
784 } ----
785 char Prefix = Name[0]; 0
786 ----
787 // Treat the rest of the register name as a register number. ----
788 if (Name.substr(1).getAsInteger(10, Reg.Num)) { 0
789 if (RestoreOnFailure) 0
790 getLexer().UnLex(PercentTok); 0
791 return Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid register"); 0
792 } ----
793 ----
794 // Look for valid combinations of prefix and number. ----
795 if (Prefix == 'r' && Reg.Num < 16) 0
796 Reg.Group = RegGR; 0
797 else if (Prefix == 'f' && Reg.Num < 16) 0
798 Reg.Group = RegFP; 0
799 else if (Prefix == 'v' && Reg.Num < 32) 0
800 Reg.Group = RegV; 0
801 else if (Prefix == 'a' && Reg.Num < 16) 0
802 Reg.Group = RegAR; 0
803 else if (Prefix == 'c' && Reg.Num < 16) 0
804 Reg.Group = RegCR; 0
805 else { ----
806 if (RestoreOnFailure) 0
807 getLexer().UnLex(PercentTok); 0
808 return Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid register"); 0
809 } ----
810 ----
811 Reg.EndLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
812 Parser.Lex(); 0
813 return false; 0
814 } ----
815 ----
816 // Parse a register of kind Kind and add it to Operands. ----
817 OperandMatchResultTy ----
818 SystemZAsmParser::parseRegister(OperandVector &Operands, RegisterKind Kind) { 0
819 Register Reg; 0
820 RegisterGroup Group; ----
821 switch (Kind) { 0
822 case GR32Reg: 0
823 case GRH32Reg: ----
824 case GR64Reg: ----
825 case GR128Reg: ----
826 Group = RegGR; 0
827 break; 0
828 case FP32Reg: 0
829 case FP64Reg: ----
830 case FP128Reg: ----
831 Group = RegFP; 0
832 break; 0
833 case VR32Reg: 0
834 case VR64Reg: ----
835 case VR128Reg: ----
836 Group = RegV; 0
837 break; 0
838 case AR32Reg: 0
839 Group = RegAR; 0
840 break; 0
841 case CR64Reg: 0
842 Group = RegCR; 0
843 break; 0
844 } ----
845 ----
846 // Handle register names of the form % ----
847 if (isParsingATT() && Parser.getTok().is(AsmToken::Percent)) { 0
848 if (parseRegister(Reg)) 0
849 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
850 ----
851 // Check the parsed register group "Reg.Group" with the expected "Group" ----
852 // Have to error out if user specified wrong prefix. ----
853 switch (Group) { 0
854 case RegGR: 0
855 case RegFP: ----
856 case RegAR: ----
857 case RegCR: ----
858 if (Group != Reg.Group) { 0
859 Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid operand for instruction"); 0
860 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
861 } ----
862 break; 0
863 case RegV: 0
864 if (Reg.Group != RegV && Reg.Group != RegFP) { 0
865 Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid operand for instruction"); 0
866 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
867 } ----
868 break; 0
869 } ----
870 } else if (Parser.getTok().is(AsmToken::Integer)) { 0
871 if (parseIntegerRegister(Reg, Group)) 0
872 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
873 } ----
874 // Otherwise we didn't match a register operand. ----
875 else ----
876 return MatchOperand_NoMatch; 0
877 ----
878 // Determine the LLVM register number according to Kind. ----
879 const unsigned *Regs; ----
880 switch (Kind) { 0
881 case GR32Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::GR32Regs; break; 0
882 case GRH32Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::GRH32Regs; break; 0
883 case GR64Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::GR64Regs; break; 0
884 case GR128Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::GR128Regs; break; 0
885 case FP32Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::FP32Regs; break; 0
886 case FP64Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::FP64Regs; break; 0
887 case FP128Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::FP128Regs; break; 0
888 case VR32Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::VR32Regs; break; 0
889 case VR64Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::VR64Regs; break; 0
890 case VR128Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::VR128Regs; break; 0
891 case AR32Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::AR32Regs; break; 0
892 case CR64Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::CR64Regs; break; 0
893 } ----
894 if (Regs[Reg.Num] == 0) { 0
895 Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid register pair"); 0
896 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
897 } ----
898 ----
899 Operands.push_back( 0
900 SystemZOperand::createReg(Kind, Regs[Reg.Num], Reg.StartLoc, Reg.EndLoc)); 0
901 return MatchOperand_Success; 0
902 } ----
903 ----
904 // Parse any type of register (including integers) and add it to Operands. ----
905 OperandMatchResultTy ----
906 SystemZAsmParser::parseAnyRegister(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
907 SMLoc StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
908 ----
909 // Handle integer values. ----
910 if (Parser.getTok().is(AsmToken::Integer)) { 0
911 const MCExpr *Register; ----
912 if (Parser.parseExpression(Register)) 0
913 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
914 ----
915 if (auto *CE = dyn_cast(Register)) { 0
916 int64_t Value = CE->getValue(); 0
917 if (Value < 0 || Value > 15) { 0
918 Error(StartLoc, "invalid register"); 0
919 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
920 } ----
921 } ----
922 ----
923 SMLoc EndLoc = ----
924 SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1); 0
925 ----
926 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createImm(Register, StartLoc, EndLoc)); 0
927 } ----
928 else { ----
929 if (isParsingHLASM()) 0
930 return MatchOperand_NoMatch; 0
931 ----
932 Register Reg; 0
933 if (parseRegister(Reg)) 0
934 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
935 ----
936 if (Reg.Num > 15) { 0
937 Error(StartLoc, "invalid register"); 0
938 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
939 } ----
940 ----
941 // Map to the correct register kind. ----
942 RegisterKind Kind; ----
943 unsigned RegNo; ----
944 if (Reg.Group == RegGR) { 0
945 Kind = GR64Reg; 0
946 RegNo = SystemZMC::GR64Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
947 } ----
948 else if (Reg.Group == RegFP) { 0
949 Kind = FP64Reg; 0
950 RegNo = SystemZMC::FP64Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
951 } ----
952 else if (Reg.Group == RegV) { 0
953 Kind = VR128Reg; 0
954 RegNo = SystemZMC::VR128Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
955 } ----
956 else if (Reg.Group == RegAR) { 0
957 Kind = AR32Reg; 0
958 RegNo = SystemZMC::AR32Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
959 } ----
960 else if (Reg.Group == RegCR) { 0
961 Kind = CR64Reg; 0
962 RegNo = SystemZMC::CR64Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
963 } ----
964 else { ----
965 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
966 } ----
967 ----
968 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createReg(Kind, RegNo, 0
969 Reg.StartLoc, Reg.EndLoc)); ----
970 } ----
971 return MatchOperand_Success; 0
972 } ----
973 ----
974 bool SystemZAsmParser::parseIntegerRegister(Register &Reg, 0
975 RegisterGroup Group) { ----
976 Reg.StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
977 // We have an integer token ----
978 const MCExpr *Register; ----
979 if (Parser.parseExpression(Register)) 0
980 return true; 0
981 ----
982 const auto *CE = dyn_cast(Register); 0
983 if (!CE) 0
984 return true; 0
985 ----
986 int64_t MaxRegNum = (Group == RegV) ? 31 : 15; 0
987 int64_t Value = CE->getValue(); 0
988 if (Value < 0 || Value > MaxRegNum) { 0
989 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "invalid register"); 0
990 return true; 0
991 } ----
992 ----
993 // Assign the Register Number ----
994 Reg.Num = (unsigned)Value; 0
995 Reg.Group = Group; 0
996 Reg.EndLoc = SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1); 0
997 ----
998 // At this point, successfully parsed an integer register. ----
999 return false; 0
1000 } ----
1001 ----
1002 // Parse a memory operand into Reg1, Reg2, Disp, and Length. ----
1003 bool SystemZAsmParser::parseAddress(bool &HaveReg1, Register &Reg1, 0
1004 bool &HaveReg2, Register &Reg2, ----
1005 const MCExpr *&Disp, const MCExpr *&Length, ----
1006 bool HasLength, bool HasVectorIndex) { ----
1007 // Parse the displacement, which must always be present. ----
1008 if (getParser().parseExpression(Disp)) 0
1009 return true; 0
1010 ----
1011 // Parse the optional base and index. ----
1012 HaveReg1 = false; 0
1013 HaveReg2 = false; 0
1014 Length = nullptr; 0
1015 ----
1016 // If we have a scenario as below: ----
1017 // vgef %v0, 0(0), 0 ----
1018 // This is an example of a "BDVMem" instruction type. ----
1019 // ----
1020 // So when we parse this as an integer register, the register group ----
1021 // needs to be tied to "RegV". Usually when the prefix is passed in ----
1022 // as % its easy to check which group it should belong to ----
1023 // However, if we're passing in just the integer there's no real way to ----
1024 // "check" what register group it should belong to. ----
1025 // ----
1026 // When the user passes in the register as an integer, the user assumes that ----
1027 // the compiler is responsible for substituting it as the right kind of ----
1028 // register. Whereas, when the user specifies a "prefix", the onus is on ----
1029 // the user to make sure they pass in the right kind of register. ----
1030 // ----
1031 // The restriction only applies to the first Register (i.e. Reg1). Reg2 is ----
1032 // always a general register. Reg1 should be of group RegV if "HasVectorIndex" ----
1033 // (i.e. insn is of type BDVMem) is true. ----
1034 RegisterGroup RegGroup = HasVectorIndex ? RegV : RegGR; 0
1035 ----
1036 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::LParen)) { 0
1037 Parser.Lex(); 0
1038 ----
1039 if (isParsingATT() && getLexer().is(AsmToken::Percent)) { 0
1040 // Parse the first register. ----
1041 HaveReg1 = true; 0
1042 if (parseRegister(Reg1)) 0
1043 return true; 0
1044 } ----
1045 // So if we have an integer as the first token in ([tok1], ..), it could: ----
1046 // 1. Refer to a "Register" (i.e X,R,V fields in BD[X|R|V]Mem type of ----
1047 // instructions) ----
1048 // 2. Refer to a "Length" field (i.e L field in BDLMem type of instructions) ----
1049 else if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::Integer)) { 0
1050 if (HasLength) { 0
1051 // Instruction has a "Length" field, safe to parse the first token as ----
1052 // the "Length" field ----
1053 if (getParser().parseExpression(Length)) 0
1054 return true; 0
1055 } else { ----
1056 // Otherwise, if the instruction has no "Length" field, parse the ----
1057 // token as a "Register". We don't have to worry about whether the ----
1058 // instruction is invalid here, because the caller will take care of ----
1059 // error reporting. ----
1060 HaveReg1 = true; 0
1061 if (parseIntegerRegister(Reg1, RegGroup)) 0
1062 return true; 0
1063 } ----
1064 } else { ----
1065 // If its not an integer or a percent token, then if the instruction ----
1066 // is reported to have a "Length" then, parse it as "Length". ----
1067 if (HasLength) { 0
1068 if (getParser().parseExpression(Length)) 0
1069 return true; 0
1070 } ----
1071 } ----
1072 ----
1073 // Check whether there's a second register. ----
1074 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::Comma)) { 0
1075 Parser.Lex(); 0
1076 HaveReg2 = true; 0
1077 ----
1078 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::Integer)) { 0
1079 if (parseIntegerRegister(Reg2, RegGR)) 0
1080 return true; 0
1081 } else { ----
1082 if (isParsingATT() && parseRegister(Reg2)) 0
1083 return true; 0
1084 } ----
1085 } ----
1086 ----
1087 // Consume the closing bracket. ----
1088 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::RParen)) 0
1089 return Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "unexpected token in address"); 0
1090 Parser.Lex(); 0
1091 } ----
1092 return false; 0
1093 } ----
1094 ----
1095 // Verify that Reg is a valid address register (base or index). ----
1096 bool ----
1097 SystemZAsmParser::parseAddressRegister(Register &Reg) { 0
1098 if (Reg.Group == RegV) { 0
1099 Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid use of vector addressing"); 0
1100 return true; 0
1101 } else if (Reg.Group != RegGR) { 0
1102 Error(Reg.StartLoc, "invalid address register"); 0
1103 return true; 0
1104 } ----
1105 return false; 0
1106 } ----
1107 ----
1108 // Parse a memory operand and add it to Operands. The other arguments ----
1109 // are as above. ----
1110 OperandMatchResultTy ----
1111 SystemZAsmParser::parseAddress(OperandVector &Operands, MemoryKind MemKind, 0
1112 RegisterKind RegKind) { ----
1113 SMLoc StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
1114 unsigned Base = 0, Index = 0, LengthReg = 0; 0
1115 Register Reg1, Reg2; 0
1116 bool HaveReg1, HaveReg2; ----
1117 const MCExpr *Disp; ----
1118 const MCExpr *Length; ----
1119 ----
1120 bool HasLength = (MemKind == BDLMem) ? true : false; 0
1121 bool HasVectorIndex = (MemKind == BDVMem) ? true : false; 0
1122 if (parseAddress(HaveReg1, Reg1, HaveReg2, Reg2, Disp, Length, HasLength, 0
1123 HasVectorIndex)) ----
1124 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1125 ----
1126 const unsigned *Regs; ----
1127 switch (RegKind) { 0
1128 case GR32Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::GR32Regs; break; 0
1129 case GR64Reg: Regs = SystemZMC::GR64Regs; break; 0
1130 default: llvm_unreachable("invalid RegKind"); 0
1131 } ----
1132 ----
1133 switch (MemKind) { 0
1134 case BDMem: 0
1135 // If we have Reg1, it must be an address register. ----
1136 if (HaveReg1) { 0
1137 if (parseAddressRegister(Reg1)) 0
1138 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1139 Base = Regs[Reg1.Num]; 0
1140 } ----
1141 // There must be no Reg2. ----
1142 if (HaveReg2) { 0
1143 Error(StartLoc, "invalid use of indexed addressing"); 0
1144 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1145 } ----
1146 break; 0
1147 case BDXMem: 0
1148 // If we have Reg1, it must be an address register. ----
1149 if (HaveReg1) { 0
1150 if (parseAddressRegister(Reg1)) 0
1151 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1152 // If the are two registers, the first one is the index and the ----
1153 // second is the base. ----
1154 if (HaveReg2) 0
1155 Index = Regs[Reg1.Num]; 0
1156 else ----
1157 Base = Regs[Reg1.Num]; 0
1158 } ----
1159 // If we have Reg2, it must be an address register. ----
1160 if (HaveReg2) { 0
1161 if (parseAddressRegister(Reg2)) 0
1162 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1163 Base = Regs[Reg2.Num]; 0
1164 } ----
1165 break; 0
1166 case BDLMem: 0
1167 // If we have Reg2, it must be an address register. ----
1168 if (HaveReg2) { 0
1169 if (parseAddressRegister(Reg2)) 0
1170 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1171 Base = Regs[Reg2.Num]; 0
1172 } ----
1173 // We cannot support base+index addressing. ----
1174 if (HaveReg1 && HaveReg2) { 0
1175 Error(StartLoc, "invalid use of indexed addressing"); 0
1176 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1177 } ----
1178 // We must have a length. ----
1179 if (!Length) { 0
1180 Error(StartLoc, "missing length in address"); 0
1181 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1182 } ----
1183 break; 0
1184 case BDRMem: 0
1185 // We must have Reg1, and it must be a GPR. ----
1186 if (!HaveReg1 || Reg1.Group != RegGR) { 0
1187 Error(StartLoc, "invalid operand for instruction"); 0
1188 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1189 } ----
1190 LengthReg = SystemZMC::GR64Regs[Reg1.Num]; 0
1191 // If we have Reg2, it must be an address register. ----
1192 if (HaveReg2) { 0
1193 if (parseAddressRegister(Reg2)) 0
1194 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1195 Base = Regs[Reg2.Num]; 0
1196 } ----
1197 break; 0
1198 case BDVMem: 0
1199 // We must have Reg1, and it must be a vector register. ----
1200 if (!HaveReg1 || Reg1.Group != RegV) { 0
1201 Error(StartLoc, "vector index required in address"); 0
1202 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1203 } ----
1204 Index = SystemZMC::VR128Regs[Reg1.Num]; 0
1205 // If we have Reg2, it must be an address register. ----
1206 if (HaveReg2) { 0
1207 if (parseAddressRegister(Reg2)) 0
1208 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1209 Base = Regs[Reg2.Num]; 0
1210 } ----
1211 break; 0
1212 } ----
1213 ----
1214 SMLoc EndLoc = ----
1215 SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1); 0
1216 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createMem(MemKind, RegKind, Base, Disp, 0
1217 Index, Length, LengthReg, ----
1218 StartLoc, EndLoc)); ----
1219 return MatchOperand_Success; 0
1220 } ----
1221 ----
1222 ParseStatus SystemZAsmParser::parseDirective(AsmToken DirectiveID) { 0
1223 StringRef IDVal = DirectiveID.getIdentifier(); 0
1224 ----
1225 if (IDVal == ".insn") 0
1226 return ParseDirectiveInsn(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
1227 if (IDVal == ".machine") 0
1228 return ParseDirectiveMachine(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
1229 if (IDVal.startswith(".gnu_attribute")) 0
1230 return ParseGNUAttribute(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
1231 ----
1232 return ParseStatus::NoMatch; 0
1233 } ----
1234 ----
1235 /// ParseDirectiveInsn ----
1236 /// ::= .insn [ format, encoding, (operands (, operands)*) ] ----
1237 bool SystemZAsmParser::ParseDirectiveInsn(SMLoc L) { 0
1238 MCAsmParser &Parser = getParser(); 0
1239 ----
1240 // Expect instruction format as identifier. ----
1241 StringRef Format; 0
1242 SMLoc ErrorLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
1243 if (Parser.parseIdentifier(Format)) 0
1244 return Error(ErrorLoc, "expected instruction format"); 0
1245 ----
1246 SmallVector, 8> Operands; 0
1247 ----
1248 // Find entry for this format in InsnMatchTable. ----
1249 auto EntryRange = ----
1250 std::equal_range(std::begin(InsnMatchTable), std::end(InsnMatchTable), 0
1251 Format, CompareInsn()); ----
1252 ----
1253 // If first == second, couldn't find a match in the table. ----
1254 if (EntryRange.first == EntryRange.second) 0
1255 return Error(ErrorLoc, "unrecognized format"); 0
1256 ----
1257 struct InsnMatchEntry *Entry = EntryRange.first; 0
1258 ----
1259 // Format should match from equal_range. ----
1260 assert(Entry->Format == Format); 0
1261 ----
1262 // Parse the following operands using the table's information. ----
1263 for (int i = 0; i < Entry->NumOperands; i++) { 0
1264 MatchClassKind Kind = Entry->OperandKinds[i]; 0
1265 ----
1266 SMLoc StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
1267 ----
1268 // Always expect commas as separators for operands. ----
1269 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::Comma)) 0
1270 return Error(StartLoc, "unexpected token in directive"); 0
1271 Lex(); 0
1272 ----
1273 // Parse operands. ----
1274 OperandMatchResultTy ResTy; ----
1275 if (Kind == MCK_AnyReg) 0
1276 ResTy = parseAnyReg(Operands); 0
1277 else if (Kind == MCK_VR128) 0
1278 ResTy = parseVR128(Operands); 0
1279 else if (Kind == MCK_BDXAddr64Disp12 || Kind == MCK_BDXAddr64Disp20) 0
1280 ResTy = parseBDXAddr64(Operands); 0
1281 else if (Kind == MCK_BDAddr64Disp12 || Kind == MCK_BDAddr64Disp20) 0
1282 ResTy = parseBDAddr64(Operands); 0
1283 else if (Kind == MCK_BDVAddr64Disp12) 0
1284 ResTy = parseBDVAddr64(Operands); 0
1285 else if (Kind == MCK_PCRel32) 0
1286 ResTy = parsePCRel32(Operands); 0
1287 else if (Kind == MCK_PCRel16) 0
1288 ResTy = parsePCRel16(Operands); 0
1289 else { ----
1290 // Only remaining operand kind is an immediate. ----
1291 const MCExpr *Expr; ----
1292 SMLoc StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
1293 ----
1294 // Expect immediate expression. ----
1295 if (Parser.parseExpression(Expr)) 0
1296 return Error(StartLoc, "unexpected token in directive"); 0
1297 ----
1298 SMLoc EndLoc = ----
1299 SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1); 0
1300 ----
1301 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createImm(Expr, StartLoc, EndLoc)); 0
1302 ResTy = MatchOperand_Success; 0
1303 } ----
1304 ----
1305 if (ResTy != MatchOperand_Success) 0
1306 return true; 0
1307 } ----
1308 ----
1309 // Build the instruction with the parsed operands. ----
1310 MCInst Inst = MCInstBuilder(Entry->Opcode); 0
1311 ----
1312 for (size_t i = 0; i < Operands.size(); i++) { 0
1313 MCParsedAsmOperand &Operand = *Operands[i]; 0
1314 MatchClassKind Kind = Entry->OperandKinds[i]; 0
1315 ----
1316 // Verify operand. ----
1317 unsigned Res = validateOperandClass(Operand, Kind); 0
1318 if (Res != Match_Success) 0
1319 return Error(Operand.getStartLoc(), "unexpected operand type"); 0
1320 ----
1321 // Add operands to instruction. ----
1322 SystemZOperand &ZOperand = static_cast(Operand); 0
1323 if (ZOperand.isReg()) 0
1324 ZOperand.addRegOperands(Inst, 1); 0
1325 else if (ZOperand.isMem(BDMem)) 0
1326 ZOperand.addBDAddrOperands(Inst, 2); 0
1327 else if (ZOperand.isMem(BDXMem)) 0
1328 ZOperand.addBDXAddrOperands(Inst, 3); 0
1329 else if (ZOperand.isMem(BDVMem)) 0
1330 ZOperand.addBDVAddrOperands(Inst, 3); 0
1331 else if (ZOperand.isImm()) 0
1332 ZOperand.addImmOperands(Inst, 1); 0
1333 else ----
1334 llvm_unreachable("unexpected operand type"); 0
1335 } ----
1336 ----
1337 // Emit as a regular instruction. ----
1338 Parser.getStreamer().emitInstruction(Inst, getSTI()); 0
1339 ----
1340 return false; 0
1341 } 0
1342 ----
1343 /// ParseDirectiveMachine ----
1344 /// ::= .machine [ mcpu ] ----
1345 bool SystemZAsmParser::ParseDirectiveMachine(SMLoc L) { 0
1346 MCAsmParser &Parser = getParser(); 0
1347 if (Parser.getTok().isNot(AsmToken::Identifier) && 0
1348 Parser.getTok().isNot(AsmToken::String)) 0
1349 return TokError("unexpected token in '.machine' directive"); 0
1350 ----
1351 StringRef CPU = Parser.getTok().getIdentifier(); 0
1352 Parser.Lex(); 0
1353 if (parseEOL()) 0
1354 return true; 0
1355 ----
1356 MCSubtargetInfo &STI = copySTI(); 0
1357 STI.setDefaultFeatures(CPU, /*TuneCPU*/ CPU, ""); 0
1358 setAvailableFeatures(ComputeAvailableFeatures(STI.getFeatureBits())); 0
1359 ----
1360 getTargetStreamer().emitMachine(CPU); 0
1361 ----
1362 return false; 0
1363 } ----
1364 ----
1365 bool SystemZAsmParser::ParseGNUAttribute(SMLoc L) { 0
1366 int64_t Tag; ----
1367 int64_t IntegerValue; ----
1368 if (!Parser.parseGNUAttribute(L, Tag, IntegerValue)) 0
1369 return Error(L, "malformed .gnu_attribute directive"); 0
1370 ----
1371 // Tag_GNU_S390_ABI_Vector tag is '8' and can be 0, 1, or 2. ----
1372 if (Tag != 8 || (IntegerValue < 0 || IntegerValue > 2)) 0
1373 return Error(L, "unrecognized .gnu_attribute tag/value pair."); 0
1374 ----
1375 Parser.getStreamer().emitGNUAttribute(Tag, IntegerValue); 0
1376 ----
1377 return parseEOL(); 0
1378 } ----
1379 ----
1380 bool SystemZAsmParser::ParseRegister(MCRegister &RegNo, SMLoc &StartLoc, 0
1381 SMLoc &EndLoc, bool RestoreOnFailure) { ----
1382 Register Reg; 0
1383 if (parseRegister(Reg, RestoreOnFailure)) 0
1384 return true; 0
1385 if (Reg.Group == RegGR) 0
1386 RegNo = SystemZMC::GR64Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
1387 else if (Reg.Group == RegFP) 0
1388 RegNo = SystemZMC::FP64Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
1389 else if (Reg.Group == RegV) 0
1390 RegNo = SystemZMC::VR128Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
1391 else if (Reg.Group == RegAR) 0
1392 RegNo = SystemZMC::AR32Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
1393 else if (Reg.Group == RegCR) 0
1394 RegNo = SystemZMC::CR64Regs[Reg.Num]; 0
1395 StartLoc = Reg.StartLoc; 0
1396 EndLoc = Reg.EndLoc; 0
1397 return false; 0
1398 } ----
1399 ----
1400 bool SystemZAsmParser::parseRegister(MCRegister &RegNo, SMLoc &StartLoc, 0
1401 SMLoc &EndLoc) { ----
1402 return ParseRegister(RegNo, StartLoc, EndLoc, /*RestoreOnFailure=*/false); 0
1403 } ----
1404 ----
1405 OperandMatchResultTy SystemZAsmParser::tryParseRegister(MCRegister &RegNo, 0
1406 SMLoc &StartLoc, ----
1407 SMLoc &EndLoc) { ----
1408 bool Result = ----
1409 ParseRegister(RegNo, StartLoc, EndLoc, /*RestoreOnFailure=*/true); 0
1410 bool PendingErrors = getParser().hasPendingError(); 0
1411 getParser().clearPendingErrors(); 0
1412 if (PendingErrors) 0
1413 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1414 if (Result) 0
1415 return MatchOperand_NoMatch; 0
1416 return MatchOperand_Success; 0
1417 } ----
1418 ----
1419 bool SystemZAsmParser::ParseInstruction(ParseInstructionInfo &Info, 0
1420 StringRef Name, SMLoc NameLoc, ----
1421 OperandVector &Operands) { ----
1422 ----
1423 // Apply mnemonic aliases first, before doing anything else, in ----
1424 // case the target uses it. ----
1425 applyMnemonicAliases(Name, getAvailableFeatures(), getMAIAssemblerDialect()); 0
1426 ----
1427 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createToken(Name, NameLoc)); 0
1428 ----
1429 // Read the remaining operands. ----
1430 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::EndOfStatement)) { 0
1431 // Read the first operand. ----
1432 if (parseOperand(Operands, Name)) { 0
1433 return true; 0
1434 } ----
1435 ----
1436 // Read any subsequent operands. ----
1437 while (getLexer().is(AsmToken::Comma)) { 0
1438 Parser.Lex(); 0
1439 ----
1440 if (isParsingHLASM() && getLexer().is(AsmToken::Space)) 0
1441 return Error( 0
1442 Parser.getTok().getLoc(), 0
1443 "No space allowed between comma that separates operand entries"); 0
1444 ----
1445 if (parseOperand(Operands, Name)) { 0
1446 return true; 0
1447 } ----
1448 } ----
1449 ----
1450 // Under the HLASM variant, we could have the remark field ----
1451 // The remark field occurs after the operation entries ----
1452 // There is a space that separates the operation entries and the ----
1453 // remark field. ----
1454 if (isParsingHLASM() && getTok().is(AsmToken::Space)) { 0
1455 // We've confirmed that there is a Remark field. ----
1456 StringRef Remark(getLexer().LexUntilEndOfStatement()); 0
1457 Parser.Lex(); 0
1458 ----
1459 // If there is nothing after the space, then there is nothing to emit ----
1460 // We could have a situation as this: ----
1461 // " \n" ----
1462 // After lexing above, we will have ----
1463 // "\n" ----
1464 // This isn't an explicit remark field, so we don't have to output ----
1465 // this as a comment. ----
1466 if (Remark.size()) 0
1467 // Output the entire Remarks Field as a comment ----
1468 getStreamer().AddComment(Remark); 0
1469 } ----
1470 ----
1471 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::EndOfStatement)) { 0
1472 SMLoc Loc = getLexer().getLoc(); 0
1473 return Error(Loc, "unexpected token in argument list"); 0
1474 } ----
1475 } ----
1476 ----
1477 // Consume the EndOfStatement. ----
1478 Parser.Lex(); 0
1479 return false; 0
1480 } ----
1481 ----
1482 bool SystemZAsmParser::parseOperand(OperandVector &Operands, 0
1483 StringRef Mnemonic) { ----
1484 // Check if the current operand has a custom associated parser, if so, try to ----
1485 // custom parse the operand, or fallback to the general approach. Force all ----
1486 // features to be available during the operand check, or else we will fail to ----
1487 // find the custom parser, and then we will later get an InvalidOperand error ----
1488 // instead of a MissingFeature errror. ----
1489 FeatureBitset AvailableFeatures = getAvailableFeatures(); 0
1490 FeatureBitset All; 0
1491 All.set(); 0
1492 setAvailableFeatures(All); 0
1493 OperandMatchResultTy ResTy = MatchOperandParserImpl(Operands, Mnemonic); 0
1494 setAvailableFeatures(AvailableFeatures); 0
1495 if (ResTy == MatchOperand_Success) 0
1496 return false; 0
1497 ----
1498 // If there wasn't a custom match, try the generic matcher below. Otherwise, ----
1499 // there was a match, but an error occurred, in which case, just return that ----
1500 // the operand parsing failed. ----
1501 if (ResTy == MatchOperand_ParseFail) 0
1502 return true; 0
1503 ----
1504 // Check for a register. All real register operands should have used ----
1505 // a context-dependent parse routine, which gives the required register ----
1506 // class. The code is here to mop up other cases, like those where ----
1507 // the instruction isn't recognized. ----
1508 if (isParsingATT() && Parser.getTok().is(AsmToken::Percent)) { 0
1509 Register Reg; 0
1510 if (parseRegister(Reg)) 0
1511 return true; 0
1512 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createInvalid(Reg.StartLoc, Reg.EndLoc)); 0
1513 return false; 0
1514 } ----
1515 ----
1516 // The only other type of operand is an immediate or address. As above, ----
1517 // real address operands should have used a context-dependent parse routine, ----
1518 // so we treat any plain expression as an immediate. ----
1519 SMLoc StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
1520 Register Reg1, Reg2; 0
1521 bool HaveReg1, HaveReg2; ----
1522 const MCExpr *Expr; ----
1523 const MCExpr *Length; ----
1524 if (parseAddress(HaveReg1, Reg1, HaveReg2, Reg2, Expr, Length, 0
1525 /*HasLength*/ true, /*HasVectorIndex*/ true)) ----
1526 return true; 0
1527 // If the register combination is not valid for any instruction, reject it. ----
1528 // Otherwise, fall back to reporting an unrecognized instruction. ----
1529 if (HaveReg1 && Reg1.Group != RegGR && Reg1.Group != RegV 0
1530 && parseAddressRegister(Reg1)) 0
1531 return true; 0
1532 if (HaveReg2 && parseAddressRegister(Reg2)) 0
1533 return true; 0
1534 ----
1535 SMLoc EndLoc = ----
1536 SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1); 0
1537 if (HaveReg1 || HaveReg2 || Length) 0
1538 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createInvalid(StartLoc, EndLoc)); 0
1539 else ----
1540 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createImm(Expr, StartLoc, EndLoc)); 0
1541 return false; 0
1542 } ----
1543 ----
1544 bool SystemZAsmParser::MatchAndEmitInstruction(SMLoc IDLoc, unsigned &Opcode, 0
1545 OperandVector &Operands, ----
1546 MCStreamer &Out, ----
1547 uint64_t &ErrorInfo, ----
1548 bool MatchingInlineAsm) { ----
1549 MCInst Inst; 0
1550 unsigned MatchResult; ----
1551 ----
1552 unsigned Dialect = getMAIAssemblerDialect(); 0
1553 ----
1554 FeatureBitset MissingFeatures; 0
1555 MatchResult = MatchInstructionImpl(Operands, Inst, ErrorInfo, MissingFeatures, 0
1556 MatchingInlineAsm, Dialect); ----
1557 switch (MatchResult) { 0
1558 case Match_Success: 0
1559 Inst.setLoc(IDLoc); 0
1560 Out.emitInstruction(Inst, getSTI()); 0
1561 return false; 0
1562 ----
1563 case Match_MissingFeature: { 0
1564 assert(MissingFeatures.any() && "Unknown missing feature!"); 0
1565 // Special case the error message for the very common case where only ----
1566 // a single subtarget feature is missing ----
1567 std::string Msg = "instruction requires:"; 0
1568 for (unsigned I = 0, E = MissingFeatures.size(); I != E; ++I) { 0
1569 if (MissingFeatures[I]) { 0
1570 Msg += " "; 0
1571 Msg += getSubtargetFeatureName(I); 0
1572 } ----
1573 } ----
1574 return Error(IDLoc, Msg); 0
1575 } 0
1576 ----
1577 case Match_InvalidOperand: { 0
1578 SMLoc ErrorLoc = IDLoc; 0
1579 if (ErrorInfo != ~0ULL) { 0
1580 if (ErrorInfo >= Operands.size()) 0
1581 return Error(IDLoc, "too few operands for instruction"); 0
1582 ----
1583 ErrorLoc = ((SystemZOperand &)*Operands[ErrorInfo]).getStartLoc(); 0
1584 if (ErrorLoc == SMLoc()) 0
1585 ErrorLoc = IDLoc; 0
1586 } ----
1587 return Error(ErrorLoc, "invalid operand for instruction"); 0
1588 } ----
1589 ----
1590 case Match_MnemonicFail: { 0
1591 FeatureBitset FBS = ComputeAvailableFeatures(getSTI().getFeatureBits()); 0
1592 std::string Suggestion = SystemZMnemonicSpellCheck( ----
1593 ((SystemZOperand &)*Operands[0]).getToken(), FBS, Dialect); 0
1594 return Error(IDLoc, "invalid instruction" + Suggestion, 0
1595 ((SystemZOperand &)*Operands[0]).getLocRange()); 0
1596 } 0
1597 } ----
1598 ----
1599 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected match type"); 0
1600 } 0
1601 ----
1602 OperandMatchResultTy ----
1603 SystemZAsmParser::parsePCRel(OperandVector &Operands, int64_t MinVal, 0
1604 int64_t MaxVal, bool AllowTLS) { ----
1605 MCContext &Ctx = getContext(); 0
1606 MCStreamer &Out = getStreamer(); 0
1607 const MCExpr *Expr; ----
1608 SMLoc StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
1609 if (getParser().parseExpression(Expr)) 0
1610 return MatchOperand_NoMatch; 0
1611 ----
1612 auto isOutOfRangeConstant = [&](const MCExpr *E, bool Negate) -> bool { 0
1613 if (auto *CE = dyn_cast(E)) { 0
1614 int64_t Value = CE->getValue(); 0
1615 if (Negate) 0
1616 Value = -Value; 0
1617 if ((Value & 1) || Value < MinVal || Value > MaxVal) 0
1618 return true; 0
1619 } ----
1620 return false; 0
1621 }; 0
1622 ----
1623 // For consistency with the GNU assembler, treat immediates as offsets ----
1624 // from ".". ----
1625 if (auto *CE = dyn_cast(Expr)) { 0
1626 if (isParsingHLASM()) { 0
1627 Error(StartLoc, "Expected PC-relative expression"); 0
1628 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1629 } ----
1630 if (isOutOfRangeConstant(CE, false)) { 0
1631 Error(StartLoc, "offset out of range"); 0
1632 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1633 } ----
1634 int64_t Value = CE->getValue(); 0
1635 MCSymbol *Sym = Ctx.createTempSymbol(); 0
1636 Out.emitLabel(Sym); 0
1637 const MCExpr *Base = MCSymbolRefExpr::create(Sym, MCSymbolRefExpr::VK_None, 0
1638 Ctx); ----
1639 Expr = Value == 0 ? Base : MCBinaryExpr::createAdd(Base, Expr, Ctx); 0
1640 } ----
1641 ----
1642 // For consistency with the GNU assembler, conservatively assume that a ----
1643 // constant offset must by itself be within the given size range. ----
1644 if (const auto *BE = dyn_cast(Expr)) 0
1645 if (isOutOfRangeConstant(BE->getLHS(), false) || 0
1646 isOutOfRangeConstant(BE->getRHS(), 0
1647 BE->getOpcode() == MCBinaryExpr::Sub)) { 0
1648 Error(StartLoc, "offset out of range"); 0
1649 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1650 } ----
1651 ----
1652 // Optionally match :tls_gdcall: or :tls_ldcall: followed by a TLS symbol. ----
1653 const MCExpr *Sym = nullptr; 0
1654 if (AllowTLS && getLexer().is(AsmToken::Colon)) { 0
1655 Parser.Lex(); 0
1656 ----
1657 if (Parser.getTok().isNot(AsmToken::Identifier)) { 0
1658 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "unexpected token"); 0
1659 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1660 } ----
1661 ----
1662 MCSymbolRefExpr::VariantKind Kind = MCSymbolRefExpr::VK_None; 0
1663 StringRef Name = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
1664 if (Name == "tls_gdcall") 0
1665 Kind = MCSymbolRefExpr::VK_TLSGD; 0
1666 else if (Name == "tls_ldcall") 0
1667 Kind = MCSymbolRefExpr::VK_TLSLDM; 0
1668 else { ----
1669 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "unknown TLS tag"); 0
1670 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1671 } ----
1672 Parser.Lex(); 0
1673 ----
1674 if (Parser.getTok().isNot(AsmToken::Colon)) { 0
1675 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "unexpected token"); 0
1676 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1677 } ----
1678 Parser.Lex(); 0
1679 ----
1680 if (Parser.getTok().isNot(AsmToken::Identifier)) { 0
1681 Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "unexpected token"); 0
1682 return MatchOperand_ParseFail; 0
1683 } ----
1684 ----
1685 StringRef Identifier = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
1686 Sym = MCSymbolRefExpr::create(Ctx.getOrCreateSymbol(Identifier), 0
1687 Kind, Ctx); ----
1688 Parser.Lex(); 0
1689 } ----
1690 ----
1691 SMLoc EndLoc = ----
1692 SMLoc::getFromPointer(Parser.getTok().getLoc().getPointer() - 1); 0
1693 ----
1694 if (AllowTLS) 0
1695 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createImmTLS(Expr, Sym, 0
1696 StartLoc, EndLoc)); ----
1697 else ----
1698 Operands.push_back(SystemZOperand::createImm(Expr, StartLoc, EndLoc)); 0
1699 ----
1700 return MatchOperand_Success; 0
1701 } ----
1702 ----
1703 bool SystemZAsmParser::isLabel(AsmToken &Token) { 0
1704 if (isParsingATT()) 0
1705 return true; 0
1706 ----
1707 // HLASM labels are ordinary symbols. ----
1708 // An HLASM label always starts at column 1. ----
1709 // An ordinary symbol syntax is laid out as follows: ----
1710 // Rules: ----
1711 // 1. Has to start with an "alphabetic character". Can be followed by up to ----
1712 // 62 alphanumeric characters. An "alphabetic character", in this scenario, ----
1713 // is a letter from 'A' through 'Z', or from 'a' through 'z', ----
1714 // or '$', '_', '#', or '@' ----
1715 // 2. Labels are case-insensitive. E.g. "lab123", "LAB123", "lAb123", etc. ----
1716 // are all treated as the same symbol. However, the processing for the case ----
1717 // folding will not be done in this function. ----
1718 StringRef RawLabel = Token.getString(); 0
1719 SMLoc Loc = Token.getLoc(); 0
1720 ----
1721 // An HLASM label cannot be empty. ----
1722 if (!RawLabel.size()) 0
1723 return !Error(Loc, "HLASM Label cannot be empty"); 0
1724 ----
1725 // An HLASM label cannot exceed greater than 63 characters. ----
1726 if (RawLabel.size() > 63) 0
1727 return !Error(Loc, "Maximum length for HLASM Label is 63 characters"); 0
1728 ----
1729 // A label must start with an "alphabetic character". ----
1730 if (!isHLASMAlpha(RawLabel[0])) 0
1731 return !Error(Loc, "HLASM Label has to start with an alphabetic " 0
1732 "character or the underscore character"); 0
1733 ----
1734 // Now, we've established that the length is valid ----
1735 // and the first character is alphabetic. ----
1736 // Check whether remaining string is alphanumeric. ----
1737 for (unsigned I = 1; I < RawLabel.size(); ++I) 0
1738 if (!isHLASMAlnum(RawLabel[I])) 0
1739 return !Error(Loc, "HLASM Label has to be alphanumeric"); 0
1740 ----
1741 return true; 0
1742 } ----
1743 ----
1744 // Force static initialization. ----

705 static void printMCExpr(const MCExpr *E, raw_ostream &OS) { 705 static void printMCExpr(const MCExpr *E, raw_ostream &OS) {
706 if (!E) 706 if (!E)
707 return; 707 return;
708 if (auto *CE = dyn_cast(E)) 708 if (auto *CE = dyn_cast(E))
709 OS << *CE; 709 OS << *CE;
710 else if (auto *UE = dyn_cast(E)) 710 else if (auto *UE = dyn_cast(E))
711 OS << *UE; 711 OS << *UE;
712 else if (auto *BE = dyn_cast(E)) 712 else if (auto *BE = dyn_cast(E))
713 OS << *BE; 713 OS << *BE;
714 else if (auto *SRE = dyn_cast(E)) 714 else if (auto *SRE = dyn_cast(E))
715 OS << *SRE; 715 OS << *SRE;
716 else 716 else
717 OS << *E; 717 OS << *E;
718 } 718 }
